2014-03-17 16:34:54	smrtz|nix	http://sprunge.us/ tuftedocelot 
2014-03-17 16:35:10	smrtz|nix	tuftedocelot: sorry: http://sprunge.us/ATaJ
2014-03-17 16:36:24	tuftedocelot	You're adding the path after bspwm has already started and launched the panel. Put the two lines above exec bspwm
2014-03-17 16:37:13	smrtz|nix	oh, ok.
2014-03-17 16:40:38	smrtz|nix	tuftedocelot: yep, that fixed it.
2014-03-17 16:40:41	smrtz|nix	thanks for the help.
2014-03-17 16:46:14	smrtz|nix	tuftedocelot: but now my curser is messed up, like, it's only the arrow on desktop one, it's an "x" on all the others.
2014-03-17 16:49:27	tuftedocelot	try: xsetroot -cursor_name left_ptr &
2014-03-17 16:50:24	smrtz|nix	thanks.
2014-03-17 16:55:40	-->	shelvacu (~user@50-46-108-7.evrt.wa.frontiernet.net) has joined #bspwm
2014-03-17 16:56:53	shelvacu	How do I set background color/image for bspwm?
2014-03-17 17:00:20	smrtz|nix	awesome, thanks tuftedocelot 
2014-03-17 17:03:47	shelvacu	Anyone? I haven't been able to figure it out.
2014-03-17 17:05:37	shelvacu	I feel like I'm missing something obvious
2014-03-17 17:09:00	shelvacu	A google search for "bspwm background image" gives a bunch of images of bspwm desktops with backgrounds
2014-03-17 17:09:26	shelvacu	it's like google is just taunting me
2014-03-17 17:11:54	tbuck	shelvacu: its becuase theres no specific way to do it for bspwm
2014-03-17 17:12:07	tbuck	youre setting the background of the root X window
2014-03-17 17:12:15	tbuck	check for some X background setters
2014-03-17 17:13:19	tbuck	i prefer hsetroot, feh works too. for solid colors xsetroot works fine
2014-03-17 17:13:31	shelvacu	thank you, that should get me in the right mindset
2014-03-17 17:18:50	shelvacu	so many choices
